        usernameInput.sendKeys(username);
        passwordInput.sendKeys(password);
        loginButton.click();
    }
}

// Dashboard.java
public class Dashboard {
    // Locators
    private WebElement welcomeMessage = driver.findElement(By.id("welcomeMessage"));

    // Action
    public String getWelcomeMessage() {
        return welcomeMessage.getText();
    }
}


Test Script:

public class LoginTest {
    @Test
    public void successfulLogin() {
        LoginPage loginPage = new LoginPage();
        Dashboard dashboard = new Dashboard();

        loginPage.login("user1", "password123");
        String welcome = dashboard.getWelcomeMessage();

        Assert.assertEquals("Welcome, user1!", welcome);
    }
}

Assertions form the backbone of automated testing and are key to assessing
whether expected behavior in the software under test matches the actual outcome.


COMMON TYPES OF ASSERTIONS

 * Boolean Assertions: Verify the logical truth of a condition, often referred
   to as "pass" or "fail":

   * assert(condition) or assertTrue(condition)
   * Python: assert condition

 * Equality Assertions: Compare expected and actual values for equality:

   * assertEquals(expected, actual) or assertEqual(expected, actual)
   * Python: assert expected == actual

 * Nullity Assertions: Check if a value is NULL or None:

   * assertNull(object) or assertIsNone(object)
   * Python: assert object is None

 * State Assertions: Assess the state of the system before or after a test:

   * assertTrue(booleanConditionForStateCheck)
   * Python: assert some_variable > 10

 * Compounded Assertions: Combine multiple assertions, ensuring all must pass:

   * assertAll(assertion1, assertion2, assertion3) or assertThat(actual,
     matcher)
   * Python: assert expected == actual and some_variable > 0


ADVANTAGES OF ASSERTIONS IN AUTOMATED TESTING

 * Simplicity: Assertions are easy to write and comprehend.
 * Value Verification: They verify the expected values against the actual
   outputs.
 * Comparative Integrity: Assertions often halts test execution post-failure.


DISADVANTAGES OF ASSERTIONS IN AUTOMATED TESTING

 * One-and-Done Behavior: After the first failure, subsequent assertions might
   not execute if part of the same test case. This can limit the visibility into
   other potential issues.
 * Limited Detail: Provides only a high-level view of the failure without
   specific indications of what went wrong, thus requiring additional effort for
   diagnosis.


CODE EXAMPLE: USING ASSERTIONS IN JUNIT (JAVA)

Here is the Java code:

import static org.junit.Assert.*;

public class MyClassTest {
