NOTIFIERS: PROVIDING REAL-TIME INFORMATION

Notifiers alert relevant stakeholders to immediate test events. These can be as
simple as displaying notifications or as comprehensive as emailing test results
to key personnel, ensuring rapid issue identification and resolution.

Testing RESTful APIs can involve black-box, white-box, and grey-box
methodologies, ensuring all components work as expected.

Developers typically use Test Harnesses and Assertions alongside HTTP Clients
for both automated and manual testing.


KEY API TEST TYPES

 * Unit Testing isolates individual API endpoints, verifying their
   functionality, often without external dependencies.

 * Component Testing involves testing several related endpoints together.

 * Integration Testing evaluates the API's functionality as a whole, including
   its interactions with other services.

 * End-to-End Testing simulates real-world user scenarios, often through UI
   interactions, to ensure the API operates as expected in a production
   environment.


HTTP CLIENT LIBRARIES FOR TESTING

 * cURL: A command-line tool for transferring data with URL syntax; beneficial
   for manual testing.

 * Postman: A popular API client that allows for API development, testing,
   sharing, and more.

 * Spring RestTemplate: Part of the Spring Framework, it simplifies making HTTP
   requests.

 * Requests: A Python library making HTTP calls more straightforward than the
   built-in requests module.


CODE EXAMPLE: TESTING WITH SPRING RESTTEMPLATE

Here is the Java code:

import org.springframework.web.client.RestTemplate;

public class APITest {
    private RestTemplate restTemplate = new RestTemplate();
    private String apiUrl = "http://example.com/api/";

    public String getDataFromApi(String resourceId) {
        return restTemplate.getForObject(apiUrl + resourceId, String.class);
    }
}



HTTP ASSERTIONS

For RESTful API testing, build and handle assertions around HTTP methods and
status codes. Here are some examples:

 * 201 Created: Ensures that a POST request for the creation of a resource has
   been handled as expected.

 * 200 OK: Checks that a GET request was successful.


CODE EXAMPLE: HTTP ASSERTIONS WITH JUNIT & HAMCREST

Here is the Java code:

import static org.hamcrest.Matchers.*;
import static org.hamcrest.MatcherAssert.*;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.*;

@Test
public void verifyGetRequestReturnsResource() {
    String resourceData = getDataFromApi("resource/123");
    assertThat(resourceData, not(isEmptyString()));
}

Contract testing approaches API validation from a more granular perspective than
end-to-end or integration tests. It focuses on individual services, confirming
that each service both adheres to its expectations and continues to align with
its interdependent services.


KEY CONCEPTS

 * Consumer-Driven: The journey begins with the service consumer, defining the
   expected responses for a given request.
 * Service Definitions: Contracts encapsulate these expectations as a
   well-defined set of inputs, outputs, and behaviors.
 * Isolation: Each contract is validated independently, fostering modularity.
 * Bi-Directional Validation: Both the consumer and provider ensure compliance
   with the contract.


TOOLS FOR CONTRACT TESTING

 * Pact: A market leader, especially in consumer-driven contracts, offering
   support for various languages.
 * Spring Cloud Contract: Works seamlessly with projects built using the Spring
   framework.
 * Apache Avro: Particularly useful in Java-based ecosystems for handling data
   serialization.
 * IBM App Connect: A comprehensive integration platform that facilitates
   contract testing as part of its robust API management features.
 * Nix: A powerful, pure functional programming language known for its structure
   and predictable build management. It facilitates contract testing as part of
   its feature set.


CODE EXAMPLE: CONTRACT TESTING WITH PACT

Here is the Java code:

Consumer: Defines expectations.

public class ConsumerPactTest {
    private static final String URL = "http://localhost";
    private static final int PORT = 8080;

    @Rule
    public PactProviderRule provider = new PactProviderRule("animal_provider", URL, PORT, this);

    @Pact(consumer = "animal_consumer")
    public PactDefinition createFragment(PactDslWithProvider builder) {
        return builder
                .uponReceiving("a request for an animal")
                .path("/animal")
                .method("GET")
                .willRespondWith()
                .status(200)
                .body(new PactDslJsonBody()
                        .stringMatcher("name", "\\w+", "Lion")
                        .integerType("legs", 4)
                        .asBody())
                .toPact();
    }

    @Test
    @PactVerification("animal_provider")
