public class ProviderPactTest {
    private AnimalProvider animalProvider = new AnimalProvider();

    @Test
    public void validatePact() {
        // This will validate the contract from the consumer side
        PactVerificationResult pactResult = new PactVerifier()
                .provider("animal_provider", animalProvider)
                .consumer("animal_consumer", new Config() {
                    @Override
                    public String scheme() {
                        return "http";
                    }

                    @Override
                    public String host() {
                        return "localhost";
                    }
                    @Override
                    public int port() {
                        return 8080;
                    }
                })
                .hasPactWith("animal_consumer")
                .verifyBuilder().execute();

        if (pactResult instanceof PactVerificationResult.Error) {
            fail(((PactVerificationResult.Error) pactResult).getError().getMessage());
        }

        assertThat(pactResult).isExactlyInstanceOf(PactVerificationResult.Ok.class);
    }
}


In this example, the Consumer tests are bundled together and executed, providing
a generated Pact file. The Provider side then uses this Pact file to validate
the Provider's API matches the contract specified by the Consumer, ensuring
end-to-end API compatibility.

One of the most complex bugs I've encountered involved a seemingly simple user
input form that would randomly "freeze". The issue was incredibly frustrating to
diagnose and resolve.


BUG DESCRIPTION

At first glance, the bug appeared straightforward. After some form submissions,
the application would stop accepting any new data entries. The issue was neither
consistent nor reproducible, further complicating its diagnosis.


DIAGNOSIS JOURNEY

 1. Systematic Investigation: I thoroughly analyzed the different pathway
    inputs, storage mechanisms, and validation triggers. After collecting
    extensive data, patterns started emerging.

 2. Controlled Testing: By isolating specific inputs and repeating operations, I
    could pair the bug with certain scenarios.

 3. State Management Analysis: Monitoring content refreshes and its relationship
    with the forms revealed some causal connections.

 4. Layered Bug Identification: The issue seemed to originate with network
    latency manifesting within client-side JS, possibly impacting the in-memory
    data. This cascading effect made it especially challenging to pinpoint.


FINALLY, THE BUG IDENTIFICATION

Pairing timestamps with observer callbacks, I detected anomalies in state
propagation and latency, leading to the root cause: a delay in server
acknowledgment.


CODE REPRESENTATION

Here is the JavaScript code.

// Simplified latency injection mechanism
let delayed = false;
const saveData = (data) => {
  delayed = true;
  setTimeout(() => {
    delayed = false;
    console.log("Data saved successfully:", data);
  }, 5000);
};

// Observer detecting the delay and triggering a UI refresh
const dataObserver = new MutationObserver((mutationList, observer) => {
  if (delayed) {
    console.log("Server latency detected!");
    refreshUI();
  }
});

// Binding the observer
dataObserver.observe(dataElement, { attributes: true });



LESSONS LEARNED

 1. Innovative Debugging Techniques: Tailoring observers to specific components
    facilitated intricate bug detection.

 2. Gravitating Non-Apparent Relationships: A lag in server response can cascade
    through various layers of an application, disrupting expected interactions.

 3. Utilizing Shared Contexts: Understanding how different app components or
    data sources interact provides preemptive insight into potential bug
    occurrences.

 4. Maintaining Diagnostic Rigor: Even when facing a frustrating bug, methodical
    analysis, data collection, and controlled testing eventually unravel its
    underlying complexity.
